"""
theta_gamma_coupling.py
------------------------
One of the most elegant mechanisms in systems neuroscience.
 
Theta oscillations (4-8 Hz) in the hippocampus create a slow
carrier wave — about 125ms per cycle. Within each theta cycle,
multiple bursts of gamma (30-80 Hz) can occur. Each gamma burst
is short enough (15-30ms) that several of them fit within a
single theta cycle.
 
The result: the hippocampus can encode different items in
different gamma sub-windows within a single theta cycle.
This is the neural mechanism for holding multiple items in
working memory simultaneously — a temporal multiplexing strategy.
 
Lisman & Idiart (1995) first proposed this. Subsequent work
has shown it predicts memory capacity (Miller's magical number 7
±2 corresponds to roughly 7 gamma cycles per theta cycle).
Axmacher et al. (2010) showed it in humans during working
memory tasks using intracranial EEG.
 
This visualization shows:
1. The raw coupled signal
2. Phase-amplitude coupling (PAC) — the comodulogram
3. Theta phase vs gamma amplitude relationship
4. Multiple-item encoding model
5. Memory load effect on coupling strength
6. Comparison: encoding vs retrieval
 
References:
  - Lisman & Idiart (1995) Science 267:1512
  - Buzsaki (2002) Neuron 33:325
  - Axmacher et al. (2010) PNAS 107:3228
  - Canolty et al. (2006) Science 313:1626  — PAC measurement
  - Jensen & Lisman (2005) Hippocampus 15:935
 
pip install matplotlib numpy scipy
"""
 
